{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613889"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:38:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:38:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16329"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16329"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.05,0.05,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9020"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116449"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9020"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98448"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7515"},{"type":"tags","id":"7517"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21464"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116449"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sclera is the white, opaque, outer layer of the eye that covers approximately five-sixths of the eye\u0027s surface area.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the sclera?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provides structural support and protection","Focuses light onto the retina","Produces aqueous humor","Regulates amount of light entering eye","Controls accommodation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Estructural support and protection\u003C/strong\u003E provided by the sclera is essential for maintaining the eye\u0027s shape and protecting its delicate internal structures. The sclera is composed of dense collagen and elastic fibres that give it strength and rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent functions of other ocular structures. \u003Cstrong\u003EFocusing light onto the retina\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the function of the cornea and lens. \u003Cstrong\u003EProducing aqueous humor\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of the ciliary body. \u003Cstrong\u003ERegulating amount of light entering eye\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of the iris. \u003Cstrong\u003EControlling accommodation\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of the ciliary muscles and lens. The sclera also serves as an attachment point for the extraocular muscles that control eye movement and helps maintain intraocular pressure by providing a rigid outer shell.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The sclera provides structural support and protection for the eye\u0027s internal components.","The sclera serves as an attachment point for extraocular muscles that control eye movement.","The sclera maintains the eye\u0027s shape and internal pressure."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98448"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16329"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98448"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T09:53:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T09:54:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9020"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"t